Like I say the function is actually a bunch of simple functions stuck 
together, the code is as follows:

--------------------------
            //---- Frankenstein Function #1.
            if(i1&lt;0.05)
            {    // Straight line (flat).
                return 0.1;
            }
            else if(i1&lt;0.1)
            {    // Straight line (flat).
                return 0.9;
            }
            else if(i1&lt;0.35)
            {    // Straight line (rising).
                return (i1*1.8)+0.27;
            }
            else if(i1&lt;0.5)
            {    // Sine wave troff (1/4 of a complete wave)
                return Math.Sin(((i1-0.35)*(Math.PI/0.3))-Math.PI)*0.8 + 
0.9;
            }
            else if(i1&lt;0.7)
            {    // x^4 curve.
                return Math.Pow((i1-0.5)*5, 4.0)*0.45 + 0.45;
            }
            //else if(i1&lt;1.0)
            return (1.0/((i1-0.7)*50+1.11112))*0.8 +0.1;
--------------------------

The both the input and the ouput range are 0.0 to 1.0. All of the 
scaling to this range is done within the code above which makes it less 
readable than it might be otherwise. Doing it this way simplified the 
code overall since now I can slot in any function so long as it fits 
within the correct range.

Pop size is 1000, the target # of species is set to between 40 and 50. 
The graph I posted was teh result of an overnight run, sorry I didn&#39;t 
note how many gens, quite a few though.

The fitness fn is the accumulated (and unadjusted) error for each sample 
point, of which there are 64. I therefore subtract the error from 64 to 
give a fitness, I then raise this to the power 4 to skew the fitness 
score so that a larger proportion of the is represented by good 
solutions. I then divide by 4096 to give a more human readable value of 
between 0.0 and 4096.0. The graph I posted scored around 3800 using this 
scheme which corresponds to an accumulated error of about 1.18.

